Arun wrote:
&gt; I have a testsuite which contains multiple testcases. Is it possible
&gt; to run a single test by passing a command-line option ?
&gt; 
&gt; Otherwise I have to manually comment/uncomments the testcases and
&gt; recompile the code. This is quite inefficient.

I put this in all my concrete TestCases:

   public static void main( String[] argv ) {
     if (argv.length == 0) {
       // run all of the tests
       junit.textui.TestRunner.run(suite());
     } else {
       // try to load and run each named test individually
       for (int i = 0; i &lt; argv.length; ++i) {
         String testName = argv[i];

         try {
           // run the test. it throw if the test failed, but it will if the
           // testName was invalid or couldn&#39;t be invoked.
           junit.textui.TestRunner.run(new FooTest(testName));
         } catch (Exception x) {
           System.err.println(
             &quot;The test method named &#39;&quot; + testName + &quot;&#39; could not be run: 
&quot; + x);
         }
       }
     }
   }

In other words, calling the test case from the command line with no args 
runs the entire TestSuite (however that&#39;s been defined); with one arg, 
it runs that named test only. This is a lot to type for each TestCase 
that you create, but I generate my new TestCases from a script to ease 
the pain.
